TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Comment on “Probability of Survival as an Investment Criterion” By Fred Hanssmann
AU  - Laughhunn, D. J.
Y1  - 1971/08/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.17.12.B772
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.17.12.B772
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - B-772
EP  - B-772
VL  - 17
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - In a recent article of this journal, Hanssmann [Hanssmann, Fred. 1968. Probability of survival as an investment criterion. Management Sci. 15(1, September) 33?48.] proposed probability of survival as an investment planning criterion. An earlier paper by Roy [Roy, A. D. 1952. Safety first and the holding of assets. Econometrica (July) 431?439.] has shown that the normality assumption is not necessary in order to utilize probability of survival in investment planning and that a result identical and Hanssmann's is possible in the absence of any specific assumption concerning the form of the probability distributions involved. Hence, use of probability of survival as an investment planning criterion requires only a relatively weak assumption concerning probability distributions of portfolio returns, i.e., finite means and variances. There is no need to assume normality or, for that matter, any specific form for portfolio probability distributions.
AB  - In a recent article of this journal, Hanssmann [Hanssmann, Fred. 1968. Probability of survival as an investment criterion. Management Sci. 15(1, September) 33?48.] proposed probability of survival as an investment planning criterion. An earlier paper by Roy [Roy, A. D. 1952. Safety first and the holding of assets. Econometrica (July) 431?439.] has shown that the normality assumption is not necessary in order to utilize probability of survival in investment planning and that a result identical and Hanssmann's is possible in the absence of any specific assumption concerning the form of the probability distributions involved. Hence, use of probability of survival as an investment planning criterion requires only a relatively weak assumption concerning probability distributions of portfolio returns, i.e., finite means and variances. There is no need to assume normality or, for that matter, any specific form for portfolio probability distributions.
